body:
Should we use English "Help" or "Support" ? I tend to think of the word support, and whatever we put in here lives in config, so figured worth a short bikeshed.

As far as I can tell in the code, by default we don't add a default now. Maybe a screenshot of default (help/support defined) can ... help :)

@jcarres-mdsol does this make sense for configuring your slack url?
@Monkeyanator thoughts on the reduced UI clutter (for lack of better word)?

@jcchavezs I think we did discuss having a reason at some point.. ex someone can put a JIRA ticket in the tag value. Good idea. basically someone can enter a choice of that tag value or nothing to just save empty.

On the other topic, I wouldn't assume it is definitely a zipkin server that's being archived to. It could be any APM, or even haystack. We can't really assume we know the link syntax, but that's what the POST-back is there for if it can work. Same as logs-url, if someone can express a query, they can populate the URL.

I'd recommend stopping there, short of bookmark service though. We already overloaded screen issues (ex #3014) so suggest we don't do too much adding of more links until there's more practice to show they are helpful. my 2p

@adriancole not sure how I missed this issue :( 

100% collection + late-sampling would be a good way to position the kafka-based storage.

Now that lens is in place I hope this issue gets bump again

There's a recent PR in presto about a feature using watcher with some decent feedback https://github.com/prestodb/presto/pull/14056 Note, they do NOT use this for credentials, they have a [different solution](https://github.com/prestodb/presto/pull/11742). Also, LINE uses something different entirely, a ZK based file abstraction named central dogma. Many spring users use spring cloud config.

Anyway if someone wants to punt a special case for ES, maybe this sketch can help you start!

```java
  static final String QUALIFIER = "zipkinElasticsearch";
  static final String PROPERTIES_SOURCE = "zipkin-server-security.properties";
  static final String USERNAME_PROP = "zipkin.storage.elasticsearch.username";
  static final String PASSWORD_PROP = "zipkin.storage.elasticsearch.password";

  // credentials need to be updated independent of the actual interceptor
  static final class BasicCredentials {
    volatile String basicCredentials;

    BasicCredentials(String username, String password) {
      if (username == null) throw new NullPointerException("username == null");
      if (password == null) throw new NullPointerException("password == null");
      updateCredentials(username, password);
    }

    void updateCredentials(String username, String password) {
      String token = username + ':' + password;
      basicCredentials = "Basic " + Base64.getEncoder().encodeToString(token.getBytes(UTF_8));
    }
  }

  // initial password is important as you need something before the watch starts
  @Bean @Qualifier(QUALIFIER)
  BasicCredentials dynamicElasticsearchBasicCredentials(
    @Value("${" + USERNAME_PROP + "}") String initialUsername,
    @Value("${" + PASSWORD_PROP + "}") String initialPassword
  ) {
    return new BasicCredentials(initialUsername, initialPassword);
  }


  // wire into the code that exists already
  @Bean @Qualifier(QUALIFIER)
  Consumer<ClientOptionsBuilder> dynamicElasticsearchAuth(
    @Qualifier(QUALIFIER) BasicCredentials basicCredentials) {
